Report on the results of the parallel audit of the management of VAT in the Czech Republic and Germany
Foreword
The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, stresses that the auditors have the power to audit the entire public finances.
The declaration requires that the auditors have the power to examine the tax collection as much as possible.
The Organization of the European Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be an important part of public revenue.
The thematic focus of the Sixth EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the auditing of public revenues by the auditors.
One of the most important steps towards optimising the audit activities of an auditor is the development of a special strategy for auditing public revenue.
This is especially true for taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.
As national economies are increasingly interlinked and interdependent, there can be a situation in which national auditors can only carry out their audit work in cooperation with the auditors of other states.
As an example, the audit of internationally organised fraud can be considered, which can lead to significant revenue losses in many states.
Cooperation between the authorities is needed in the fight against such crimes.
Auditors in this area must be prepared to work closely with each other.
The idea for an audit of VAT and the MIAS system was developed at the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn, which was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Audit Office.
In the course of a thorough preparation, the participating auditors first had to familiarise themselves with the legal framework and procedures of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.
On the basis of the evaluation of the available information, we made the selection of the test subjects for the examination planning.
Achieving the efficient and effective management of VAT is a long-standing problem and individual states (in particular the EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of VAT and create greater transparency in this area.
We are convinced that the results of our audit will not only help to improve the work of financial management, but can also form the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.
Report on the results of the parallel audit of the management of VAT in the Czech Republic and Germany
Introduction
Case number: CZ) 06 / 27 (DE) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215
Subject of examination:
(CZ) Management of VAT after the accession of the Czech Republic to the European Union
(De) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of VAT in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and 1925 / 2004
The Commission's audit objective:
(CZ) The aim of the audit in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures used by the financial administration in the field of VAT following the integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (hereinafter "EC") with the free movement of goods and services, as well as the use of MIAS1, in particular the control of the use of the VAT exemption for intra-Community deliveries.
(De) The aim of the audit was to examine the system of intra-Community VAT control, with a focus on mutual assistance in the area of VAT, in accordance with the above-mentioned regulations.
As a result of the audit, weaknesses should be identified and recommendations made to remedy them.
The audits were carried out jointly by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic ("NKÚ") and the Federal Court of Justice ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany on the basis of an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006.
The cooperation focused on the review of selected business transactions between entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the utilisation of information obtained through international mutual assistance between financial administrations and the comparison of sales tax management systems in the two states.
A joint final report on the results of the tests was prepared in accordance with the European guideline No 31 for the implementation of the INTOSAI exam standards.
The audited period covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.
Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel audit
The parallel audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two auditors.
In addition to the focus on "exchange of information" in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and Commission Regulation 1925 / 2004, other closely related aspects have also been examined, such as the registration of taxable persons, tax returns and summary notifications.
In addition, the audit also covered the legal situation for cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach and the comparison of statistical data.
When comparing the systems of sales tax administrations in the two countries, differences were found in the following areas:
1) Registration for VAT purposes.
While in Germany, entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among other things, the key criterion for registering is exceeding the turnover threshold set out in the VAT law.
In the Czech Republic, taxpayers receive only one tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, the taxable person receives a tax number valid only for domestic sales for the purposes of VAT.
If the German tax collector wants to make intra-Community transactions, he must apply for a special identification number, the so-called VAT ID number.
As problems arise from the different registration procedures, the rules should be harmonised within the EC (see 4.1).
2) Cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach.
In the Czech Republic, cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach is tax-free, but there is a right to deduct VAT.
In Germany, as far as the route passes through Germany, the transport service is subject to sales tax.
Efforts should be made at EC level to unify the situation under Article 393 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common turnover tax system (see 4.2).
3) Tax returns.
While in the Czech Republic, taxable income tax returns only have to be issued for under-year tax periods (month or quarter), taxable persons in Germany (monthly or quarterly)
Advance sales tax filings and a return on sales tax after the end of the calendar year.
In contrast to the Czech Republic, tax payers in Germany are required to submit VAT advance applications electronically.
The introduction of the electronic levy of VAT declarations in the Czech Republic would improve the efficiency of the Czech financial administration (see 4.3).
4) Summary messages.
While the tax authorities in the Czech Republic have to submit their summary reports to the tax authorities (fä), German tax authorities have to submit the summary reports to the CLO2.
Accordingly, in the Czech Republic, the information from the summary reports will be available immediately after their submission.
In German, the information from the summary messages is only available after their processing by the Clo.
In order to combat VAT fraud, updated information on intra-Community sales is needed as soon as possible.
The monthly submission of summary reports would shorten the period between the time of turnover and the updating of MIAS data.
This would allow for a timely review of taxation in the Member State of the acquirer (see 4.4), but only if all EC Member States introduce the same deadlines.
5) International exchange of information in the area of VAT.
In case of requests for information, the Czech Clo will monitor compliance with the three-month period.
The German Clo does not monitor processing times.
As a result, the German financial administration has completed a significantly lower percentage of requests for information within the specified period.
Because of these problems, the BRH has recommended that the German Clo be constantly monitored (see 4.6).
6) Risk management.
Each of the two Member States is in the process of developing its own risk management system (RMS) with corresponding strengths and weaknesses.
The NKÚ and the BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by a Member State alone.
Successful criteria, elements or approaches of an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in all EC Member States, otherwise fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5).
As part of the cooperation, the two auditors examined selected cases of intra-Community transactions between Czech and German tax entities.
Of these, 31 cases were jointly reviewed using the legal options of the Clo, where there were doubts about the correct taxation or suspicion of VAT fraud.
The auditors found that:
In some cases, the fä used the information obtained in the international exchange of information and re-established the VAT liability of the tax authorities concerned.
In these cases, the tax-payers had either unlawfully claimed the VAT exemption or failed to declare the purchase of goods in their VAT return.
In some cases, the fä could not use the information obtained in the exchange of information because it was incomplete or incomprehensible.
In other cases, the information could not be used because of different legal provisions in the two Member States.
In some cases, the financial management of another Member State refused to provide the information requested.
A number of cases have been uncovered in which tax payers incorrectly reported sales in their summary reports.
As a result, the data in the MIAS were correspondingly faulty, so that in these cases, the technical staff (the FA) had to investigate (see 6).
Examination procedure
Examination procedure in the CR
The audit was carried out between June 2006 and March 2007 by Division II - "State Budget Revenue" and the Territorial Examination Departments of Central Bohemia, Northwest Bohemia, South Bohemia, South Moravia, Central Moravia and North Moravia.
The audited bodies were: The Ministry of Finance and the 10 departments Humpolec, Jihlava, Kadaň, Liberec, Nymburk, Otrokovice, Prague 1, Prague 4, Sokolov and Třinec.
The College of NKÚ approved the audit findings on 23 April 2007.
Examination procedures in Germany
The audit was carried out between July 2006 and February 2007 by the Traffic Tax Examination Unit and employees of the associated PÄB Berlin, Frankfurt / Main and Munich.
It was part of the work plan for 2006 and was therefore announced to the Federal Ministry of Finance (BMF) in 2006.
After a test phase, the actual test began in the 4th quarter of 2006.
In accordance with the cases selected by the BRH and later by the NKÚ, the BRH had to announce the audit in several federal states.
Apart from interviews in the BMF and the Clo, the exam was conducted in the following federal states:
Baden-Württemberg, Bavaria, Hamburg, Lower Saxony, North Rhine-Westphalia, Rhineland-Palatinate and Saxony.
Tax records from the following subjects were included in the audit:
Bruchsal, Ettlingen, Freudenstadt, Karlsruhe City, Leonberg, Mühlacker, Singen, Tuttlingen, Cham, Fürstenfeldbruck, Munich bodies, Munich II, IV and Munich V, Starnberg, Hamburg-Altona, Hamburg-Hansa, Hamburg-Mitte, Hamburg-Nord and Hamburg for large companies, Hanover North, Winsen-Luhe, Bonn-Innenstadt, Cologne-Mitte, Cologne-Porz, Cologne-Süd, Sankt Augustin, Pirmasens, Bautzen, Chemnitz-Süd, Dresden II, Freiberg, Leipzig I and Zschopau.
In addition, discussions were held with the fä Augsburg-Stadt, Aurich, Düsseldorf-Altstadt, Eisleben, Kelheim and Verden.
The results of the exam were communicated to the BMF in May 2007.
Cooperation between the two auditors
In the run-up to the parallel audit, several meetings were held by representatives of both auditors.
The participants in these meetings familiarized themselves with the organization of the financial administration, the legislation on sales tax and the system of sales tax administration in each other's country.
The subject of the test phase was agreed at the meeting in May 2006.
The results of the test phase were evaluated at the next joint meeting in August 2006.
At this meeting, a timetable for the further procedure was drawn up and the following examination topics were determined for the parallel tests: 1.
Registration of taxable persons.
2.
Cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach - legislation in the Czech Republic and Germany.
3. International exchange of information, in particular the actions of financial officials in the processing of requests for information and the review of selected problem cases mentioned in the requests for information, as well as spontaneous information between the Czech Republic and Germany.
4. Tax returns.
5.
Summary messages.
6.
Statistical information on deliveries and acquisitions between the Czech Republic and Germany.
7. Risk management in the sales tax area.
At a meeting to vote on the further examination of the NKÚ and the BRH in December 2006, both sides familiarized themselves with the examination procedure in the Czech Republic and Germany and discussed the results of the parallel tests that had already been achieved.
