On the first day of the third month after the month in which he crossed the threshold, an entrepreneur with legal domicile, registered office or business premises in the Czech Republic, whose turnover in the last 12 consecutive calendar months exceeds the amount of CZK 1,000,000, will be eligible for payment (§ 94 (1) of Law No 235 / 2004 Coll., on VAT; hereinafter "Law No 235 / 2004").
The person concerned must apply for registration within 15 days of the end of the month in which he has exceeded the registration threshold.
The current legislation does not allow the retroactive registration of a taxable person if he has exceeded the registration deadline.
An entrepreneur with legal domicile, registered office or business premises in the Czech Republic, who provides tax-deductible services or services exempt from VAT with the right to deduct VAT, must register for VAT even if his turnover does not exceed CZK 1 million, but he fulfils other requirements set out in Law No. 235 / 2004.
An entrepreneur with legal headquarters, registered office or business premises in the Czech Republic, who does not meet any of the requirements set out in the law, can voluntarily apply for VAT registration.
When the application for registration is received by the local financial officer, the registration process begins in accordance with Law No 337 / 1992.
If you want to register voluntarily for VAT, you have to specify in your application the deadline from which you apply for registration as a VAT collector.
The financial officer has to check the information provided by the entrepreneur, i.e. the completed application for registration with all investments.
If he has doubts about the information contained in it, he has to ask the applicant to explain, supplement or prove the information provided.
If the financial officer has verified that the entrepreneur meets the requirements for registration, he has to give a written notification of the registration and the allocation of a tax number.
In the communication, the financial officer must indicate the date of entry into force of the VAT registration and the investment period for the VAT.
The investment period is the calendar quarter, unless the entrepreneur's turnover for the previous calendar year has reached at least CZK 10,000,000.
If this is the case, the predisposition period is the calendar month.
An entrepreneur whose turnover has reached at least CZK 2,000,000 in the previous calendar year is entitled to choose the calendar month as the investment period and has to inform the financial officer of this change.
The issuing of a tax number in the registration notice is always constitutive.
The taxable person must provide the tax number for each communication (including payments) with the financial officer, and also in cases where a special law requires it (e.g. Law No. 235 / 2004 concerning the preparation of tax documents) 3.
The control number contains the coding "CZ" and a basic component in the form of a general identification mark.
In the case of natural persons, this is the number of the birth certificate or any other general identification mark, as far as a special law determines it. In the case of legal persons, the general identification mark is the company identification number (in accordance with the provisions of § 33 (12) of Law No. 337 / 1992).
If, despite a request from the financial officer, the entrepreneur has not fulfilled his obligations, the local financial officer has to register him on his behalf.
A notification will also be issued to the taxman.
In the Czech Republic, every entrepreneur admitted to doing business will receive a tax number for any type of tax when they first register.
This also applies to registration as a VAT payer.
In accordance with Law No. 235 / 2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, in the event of non-compliance with the VAT registration requirement, the tax officer can demand that the taxable person receive up to 10% of the proceeds from the taxable turnover, which the person concerned has made unlawfully without taxation, for the period from the date on which the entrepreneur should have been registered as a taxable person, until the date on which the registration as a taxable person was made by the financial officer (§ 98 (1) of Law No. 235 / 2004).
The payment of the fixed amount is considered a tax payment within the meaning of Section 98 (3) of Law No. 235 / 2004, i.e. it is not a fine or a fine.
If the legal requirements are met, the registration of a taxable person can be deleted for two reasons:
1)
Deletion of the registration at the request of the taxable person, i.e. mainly for the reason that the turnover does not reach the threshold for registration (§ 106 (1) of Law No. 235 / 2004).
A tax collector can request the deletion of his registration at the earliest one year after the date of entry into force specified in the registration notice.
2) deletion of registration on the grounds of office (§ 106 (7) of Law No. 235 / 2004), if: A) the taxable person has not performed in the period of 12 consecutive months and has not informed the financial officer of the reasons for this, b) the taxable person has not fulfilled his obligations under Law No. 235 / 2004, c) the previous taxable person no longer fulfils the requirements for tax treatment.
B) A person registered for tax purposes in another Member State and in the Czech Republic with no legal place of business, place of business or place of business, or a tax-exempt foreigner who provides services in the Czech Republic and has to make a tax return and pay taxes ("non-resident entrepreneur") for these services or supplies in accordance with Section 108 of Law No. 235 / 2004, will be tax-exempt with the provision of the service in question.
He must submit an application for registration with FA Prague 1 at the latest on the day of the delivery in question.
In this application, he is required to indicate all UST IDs allocated to him in other Member States or third countries.
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration later than on the day of the first taxable service provision in the Czech Republic, the Prague 1 FA will have to register him retrospectively, as he became taxable on the day of the first taxable service provision in the Czech Republic, in accordance with Law No. 235 / 2004.
In the event of a retroactive registration, the Prague 1 FA will have to request proof of performance from the companies concerned (invoices or written explanations).
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration in the Czech Republic before performing a service for the first time, the Prague 1 FA will have to ask for the submission of the performance-based contract documents.
As of December 31, 2004, 473 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered with FA Prague 1, of which 124 were from Germany. As of December 31, 2005, a total of 951 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered, of which 233 were from Germany.
In accordance with the provisions of Section 106 (9) of Law No. 235 / 2004, the financial officer is entitled to cancel the registration of a non-resident entrepreneur as of January 31 of the following calendar year if he does not accept the obligation to file tax filings or returns and to pay tax.
When examining the NKÚ, it turned out that, in the event of a tax return being issued by post with dispatch abroad on 25 January, i.e. in accordance with the mandatory deadline for filing a tax return, this declaration had not yet been received by the FA until 31 January.
In cases where these facts, which are relevant to the possibility of deletion of registration, become known to the FA later than on 31 January, it is no longer possible to delete the registration of the non-resident company for VAT in the Czech Republic in the calendar year in question.
Registration of taxable persons in Germany
In accordance with the provisions of the tax code (§ § 137, 138 AO), any business must be registered with the municipality and / or the relevant tax office.
This registration must be made no later than one month after the start of business.
The municipality will forward the application to the tax authorities.
If the relevant tax office finds that a business activity has been started but has not been registered, it can also retroactively register the taxable person from its office.
In Germany, taxable persons, regardless of whether they are resident or non-resident, are required to register for Zwekke for VAT if they meet the requirements set out in Section 2 of the German VAT Act (UStG).
This does not depend on the amount of turnover achieved.
There is no voluntary registration in Germany.
Foreign entrepreneurs have special responsibilities.
For example, for those entrepreneurs based in the Czech Republic, the ChemnitzSüd FA is responsible.
As of 30 April 2004, 295 Czech entrepreneurs were registered with the company; as of 1 March 2006, 1,050 Czech entrepreneurs were registered there.
According to the findings of the Federal Republic of Germany, these companies with special responsibilities frequently refused to register so-called bogus self-employed persons residing in the new Central and Eastern European Member States of the EC.
Since, after the accession of these ten countries to the EC, the free movement of workers is still restricted, these self-employed people tried to circumvent these restrictions by setting up their own business.
These self-employed persons do not meet the conditions set out in § 2 UStG for recognition as entrepreneurs, as they are usually dependent on a single client who determines their working time and the type of work they perform.
In order to be registered, the entrepreneur must fill out a questionnaire from the relevant FA and provide information on the company and the business activities carried out.
The questionnaire is a mandatory form for all fä in Germany.
It will be processed either in special organisational units within the fä or in the organisational units generally responsible for the tax assessment.
With the help of this pressure, a risk assessment is carried out for the individual taxpayer before the allocation of a tax number.
The structure of the tax number for domestic sales is based on certain requirements:
The first three digits are the identification number for the relevant FA, the following three (or four) digits indicate which department is responsible within the FA, the following five (or four) digits are the identification feature for the controller, the last digit is always a control digit.
If an entrepreneur wants to participate in intra-Community trade, he needs a VAT ID to be able to make tax-free intra-Community deliveries.
This will be allocated by the Clo on request if the entrepreneur is registered in Germany for sales tax purposes.
The VAT ID number is automatically allocated by the Clo when the taxable person declares intra-Community deliveries in his VAT pre-registration or in his annual VAT return.
The UST ID number is composed of the country code (DE) and a sequence of nine digits.
The registration of an entrepreneur can be deleted: 1. On request (e.g. if he ceases to do business), but only after the completion of all tax procedures (predisposition of all financial years) or 2. If the financial administration determines that he no longer runs a business.
As a rule, the validity of the VAT ID number depends on the validity of the VAT number.
In these cases, the fä must inform the Clo of the deletion of the VAT number, so that the validity of the VAT ID number can be terminated there at this time.
According to the VAT Act (§ 19 (1) UStG), domestic tax-payers do not have to pay VAT in the following cases: 1. The turnover of the previous calendar year plus the resulting sales tax has not exceeded the amount of €17,500 and 2. In the following year the amount of €50,000 is unlikely to exceed.
The so-called small business owners are not entitled to charge VAT to other entrepreneurs, nor are they entitled to deduct VAT.
Although they do not have to pay sales tax, small business owners are required to register with the tax office and make an annual sales tax return.
A small business owner can explain the non-application of § 19 (1) UStG.
This declaration is binding for the following five years.
He may then charge the VAT and deduct the VAT.
Non-resident taxpayers can appoint a fiscal representative (§ 22a UStG).
The prerequisite for this is that they only make tax-free sales and waive the deduction.
The fiscal representative fulfils the tax obligations of the foreign entrepreneur, so he does not have to register for VAT purposes.
The invoices indicate that a fiscal representative has been appointed.
Comparison and evaluation
The situation in the two countries is different.
While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the first requirement for registration (among others) is to exceed the threshold amount specified in the VAT law.
If an entrepreneur does not exceed this threshold, he can register voluntarily.
The registration process in Germany is standardized, but differences can occur due to different organisational structures in the individual federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the taxable person will receive a tax number at the time of his first registration for any tax.
In the case of registration for VAT, this tax number also applies to intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, an entrepreneur who registers for sales tax purposes will receive a tax number exclusively for domestic sales.
If the German entrepreneur wants to carry out intra-Community sales, he has to apply specifically for the allocation of a VAT ID number.
Both the NKÚ and the BRH found that the German two-tier registration system in other Member States, such as the Czech Republic, which provides a single identification number for both national VAT registration and intra-Community sales, can lead to significant misunderstandings.
On the other hand, the two-tier system allows for retroactive (national registration) in cases where the taxable person does not register his business with the municipality or the relevant FA.
This retroactive registration allows an accurate estimate of the value added tax for previous investment periods, in particular an accurate estimate of the sales tax debt.
As the different registration procedures lead to problems, the rules for the whole EC should be standardised.
The German Parliament recently approved the introduction of a tax identification number.
This is to be allocated by the Federal Central Office for Taxation to every natural person after birth.
This number applies to natural persons resident in Germany for life.
If a natural person takes up a business activity, the relevant FA will apply for a commercial tax identification number, which serves as a VAT ID number.
In the future, therefore, there should be no delay between the national registration of a taxable person and the allocation of the VAT ID number.
Work on the implementation of an IT procedure for the management of numbers has not yet been completed.
Cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach
Legislation in the Czech Republic
According to the provisions of Section 70 of Law No. 235 / 2004, since 1 May 2004, the carriage of passengers between individual Member States and between Member States and third countries in the Czech Republic has been exempt from VAT and is entitled to a deduction.
The exemption from VAT applies even if the transport is carried out by persons registered as taxable persons in other Member States or by foreigners who are taxable domestically.
The return journey is considered to be a separate transport process.
If non-resident entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic do not carry out any economic activity other than the cross-border transport of passengers by bus and coach, they are not obliged to register as taxable in the Czech Republic.
Cross-border passenger transport in the Czech Republic has been exempted from VAT in accordance with the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic, Annex V, Chapter 5 (1) (b), as stated in the text:
"For the purpose of applying Article 28 (3) (b) of Directive 77 / 388 / EEC, the Czech Republic, in accordance with paragraph 17 of Annex F of the Directive, can either maintain the tax exemption for cross-border passenger transport until the requirement of Article 28 (4) of the Directive is met or as long as the same tax exemption is applied by any of the current Member States."
The legal requirements in Germany
According to Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006, as implemented in Germany by § 3b (1) UStG, a transport service is carried out where the transport is carried out.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and cross-border passenger transport.
Only the domestic part of the transport service is taxable in Germany.
German taxation also does not distinguish between resident and non-resident (bus) entrepreneurs.
If a non-resident taxable person is transported through Germany, the part of the transport that falls on Germany is considered taxable.
Before providing its services in Germany, the non-resident entrepreneur must report his intention to provide passenger transport services to the competent FA.
This registers it for tax purposes (compare 4.1.2) and gives a special certificate for each of the buses mentioned in the application of the taxable person.
The entrepreneur must provide his taxable transport services in a German VAT return.
As of 1 March 2006, 741 Czech bus operators were registered with the Chemnitz-Süd FA.
If the transport service is provided for a domestically based entrepreneur, the non-resident taxman does not have to pay the sales tax himself to the FA.
In its place, the domestic buyer of the services has to pay the VAT to the tax office and the net amount charged to the non-resident taxpayer, which is referred to as the "transfer of tax liability" and is in line with Article 196 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC.
In addition to the registration by a non-resident tax collector and his income tax return, the German financial administration has several means of verifying the accuracy of the tax return with regard to taxable passenger transport:
Mobile customs control groups check the certificates of buses registered abroad, which are used to transport passengers through Germany.
After each test, the mobile control groups submit an inspection protocol to the relevant FA.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group can ask the bus driver to pay the VAT before continuing his journey.
The non-resident taxable person can deduct the VAT paid in this way from the tax liability stated in his VAT return.
If the FA has doubts about the accuracy of a VAT return, it can order an audit to be carried out in the FA, or it can use the means of mutual assistance referred to in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 (see point 4.6).
Even if the foreign taxpayer refuses to pay the legally set VAT, the FA may ask for assistance under Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC.
The BRH considers these means of mutual assistance in tax matters to be too costly in relation to the low income from VAT on taxable passenger transport.
In particular, the audit of the books of a non-resident taxable person incurs disproportionately high costs for the taxable person himself and for the financial administration.
The latter must examine foreign books, which require knowledge not only of the foreign language, but also of foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, such an audit can be expected to involve a higher amount of time than a resident taxable person, although the audit is limited to passenger transport in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident taxpayer must not only accept the audit rights of his national financial administration, but also those of the other Member States where he carries out passenger transport.
In addition, for each Member State in which only one passenger transport is carried out, the taxable person must meet all existing tax requirements in the various languages and on the basis of the forms provided by the financial administrations of the relevant EC Member States.
This means that the correct taxation of cross-border passenger transport services will result in a disproportionate administrative burden.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation is different in the two states.
In the Czech Republic, passenger transport between different EC Member States and between Member States and third countries is exempt from VAT under the Czech Republic's Act of Accession to the EC.
In Germany, the transport service is subject to VAT in accordance with the route of transport that is to be carried out on German territory.
If, for the first time, a non-resident tax collector provides such a transport service, he must first register it with the relevant FA.
This registers the taxable person who must declare the taxable share of the transport service in a tax return in Germany.
Law enforcement in Germany is very time-consuming.
At least three out of four Czech tax-payers registered with the Chemnitz-Süd FA have passenger transport as a business purpose.
The amount of tax in question is quite low relative to the administrative burden.
The Member States - which levy VAT in accordance with Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of VAT - have a high administrative burden in relation to the relevant amount of tax.
In order to avoid the disproportionately high cost of VAT, cross-border passenger transport should only be taxable in one Member State.
This could be the state where the transport begins or where the service provider is based.
Such a form of taxation would require an amendment to Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006.
Sales tax returns
Levy and processing of VAT returns in the Czech Republic
Unless otherwise specified by the law, even if no tax liability has been incurred, the entrepreneur will be required to file a VAT return on the pre-print provided by the Ministry of Finance within 25 days of the end of the tax period.
The tax liability will be incurred at the end of the period for issuing the VAT return. Exempt from this rule is the VAT on the import of goods in accordance with Law No. 235 / 2004. Here, the due date of the tax is determined in accordance with the customs regulations.
If there is a claim for reimbursement as a result of above-average deductible taxes, this amount will be refunded to the taxable person within 30 days of setting this deduction without having to make an application for it.
The deadline is not applied in cases where the financial officer initiates a tax procedure with regard to the tax liability of the taxable person.
According to § 73 (11) of Law No. 235 / 2004, the right to deduct taxes can be asserted at the latest with the regular tax return for the last tax period of the calendar year in which the right to deduct taxes was created.
At the end of this period, the deduction can still be claimed within three years of the end of the tax period in which the claim would have been possible for the first time.
However, this requires the submission of a supplementary VAT return.
An amendment to Act 235 / 2004, which came into force on 1 January 2005, allows the levy of a supplementary VAT return only for the period in which the claim for a deduction could have been claimed for the first time.
A tax collector must make a supplementary VAT return if: A) the sum of the corrections leads to an increase in the tax debt, b) he makes corrections by which the last known tax debt is not changed, but only previous information is changed, c) he makes corrections to the VAT rate and the tax debt in accordance with Section 49 of Law No. 235 / 2004.
A tax collector can issue a supplementary VAT return if the sum of the corrections reduces the tax liability.
The taxable person must submit the supplementary tax return by the end of the month, which follows the month in which the facts in question were established.
The sales tax declaration can be submitted electronically either via the Internet or via data carriers.
The delivery via the Internet can be done with a certified electronic signature or without it.
If it is done without an electronic signature, it must also be submitted to data carriers.
The form for the VAT return contains separate lines for indicating the value of intra-Community deliveries and purchases.
The value of related services must be specified in separate lines of the VAT return.
Some headings are used for automated primary checks within the ATIS system.
The value of the goods delivered to persons registered as taxable in other EC Member States is compared with the data provided by the Czech tax authorities in their summary reports.
The value of purchases of goods from other Member States from persons registered as taxable there is compared with the information in the summary reports of taxable persons from other EC Member States with the help of the MIAS.
Within the framework of the ATIS system, the FA will carry out a credibility assessment of the sales tax returns.
This is done automatically, as the VAT return cannot be processed without the prior audit.
The credibility assessment includes a calculation of the standards of credibility and an assessment of the risks of the sales tax returns.
In accordance with the provisions of Section 37 (1) of Law No. 337 / 1992, the FA can repeatedly impose a fine of up to CZK 2 million on persons who fail to comply with their non-monetary obligations under this or a special tax law or a decision under this law.
