Levy and processing of sales tax returns in Germany
In Germany, a distinction is made between monthly or quarterly sales tax filings and annual sales tax returns.
However, those taxable persons who are ploughed into paying VAT pre-registration must make an annual VAT return.
Even small business owners who are not ploughed into paying VAT will have to make an annual sales tax return.
The tax-payers are, in principle, obliged to submit a VAT advance notification by the 10th day after the end of the calendar quarter in which the VAT is generated (§ 18 (2) UStG).
However, in the previous year, if the VAT debt is more than €6,136, or if it is a newly founded company, the entrepreneur will be required to file monthly VAT advance applications at the latest by the 10th day after the end of the month in question.
The taxable person can also opt for the levy of monthly VAT pre-registration if he has received a refund of €6,136 in the previous year (§ 18 (2a) UStG).
If the annual sales tax is no more than €512, neither sales tax declarations nor sales tax declarations must be made.
A resulting VAT debt must be paid 10 days after the end of the tax period.
A refund can lead to a more thorough audit by the financial management.
(Statutory) deadlines for processing VAT returns and for refunding VAT overpayments do not exist.
In order to receive a timely refund, a security can be offered for the refund amount.
In principle, sales tax returns, including refunds, must be processed quickly.
The German VAT Act allows for an extension of these (levy or payment) periods (§ 18 (6) UStG).
The extension of the deadline must be requested separately.
If it is granted, the levy of VAT pre-registration and the corresponding payments may be made a month later, but in the case of monthly notifications, a special advance payment must be made.
This payment will be offset against the VAT debt established for the pre-registration period in December.
If an error is discovered, the entrepreneur must submit a corrected VAT advance notice.
There is no "supplementary" VAT return.
Once the sales tax return submitted to the tax office by 31 May of the following year has been submitted, the entrepreneur can no longer correct an incorrect VAT advance notification, but only the incorrect annual sales tax return.
Corrections to this VAT return to the benefit or disadvantage of the taxable person are possible within four years of the end of the year in which the first VAT return was issued.
After the expiry of this four-year period, a sales tax return can usually only be corrected in cases of a light-hearted tax cut or tax evasion.
The tax-payers must submit the VAT advance applications electronically.
The fä can grant exceptions to this rule in order to avoid unreasonable hardship.
The annual sales tax return can be issued either in paper form or via the Internet with or without certification.
If the levy is made without certification, the taxman must also make the declaration on paper and with his personal signature.
In the event that no VAT advance declarations or declarations are made, the financial administration is entitled to make a rough estimate of the turnover achieved by the tax-payer 6.
In the event of a late levy, the taxable person can be charged a late surcharge (up to 10% of the tax debt or up to €25,000).
In an earlier review, the BRH found that the fä often do not charge this late surcharge.
In the cases in which the fä levied the late surcharges, the amount was fixed inconsistently and arbitrarily.
The delay surcharge therefore misses its purpose of reducing the average delay, particularly when issuing the annual sales tax return.
The preprint of the VAT return contains separate lines for value information on intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions.
There are also separate lines for the provision of services.
Non-taxable sales must be stated in a separate line of the VAT return.
The sales tax returns submitted on paper must either be scanned or electronically recorded by specially designated personnel.
The data of electronically submitted tax returns are directly available to the financial administration.
