The introduction of the levy on electronic tax returns in the Czech Republic would increase the efficiency of the Czech financial administration.
Summary notifications
Submission and processing of summary notifications in the Czech Republic
In accordance with the provisions of Section 102 of Law No. 235 / 2004, an entrepreneur who delivers goods to a person registered in another Member State for tax purposes must submit corresponding summary notices (hereinafter referred to as "ZM").
The value of the delivered goods is always stated in the ZM in Czech currency, broken down according to the UST-IdNr7, the individual taxable persons under whom they are registered in the other Member State.
Information on services is not provided in the ZM.
The taxable persons with a calendar monthly or quarterly tax period have to hand over the ZM to the local FA no later than the 25th day after the end of each quarter.
Incorrect data must be corrected in an Amending ZM within 15 days of finding the error.
Faulty data in the ZM is always replaced by the data from the correction ZM.
Similar to tax returns, the tax payers can also hand over the ZM electronically.
If a tax collector does not issue a ZM or Amending ZM, although he is required to do so by law no. 235 / 2004, the financial officer has to ask him to hand over the relevant ZM, pointing out the consequences of the non-levy. In the event of non-payment of non-monetary payments, the financial officer has the power to repeatedly impose fines of up to CZK 2 million in accordance with section 37 of law no. 337 / 1992.
In its audit, the NKÚ found that the fä mostly did not use their power to impose fines on their defaulting tax payers.
In particular, in the case of the ZM levy, the tax-payers are not sufficiently motivated to fulfil their obligations, since the failure to levy a ZM does not affect the amount of their VAT debt.
In accordance with Section 102 (5) of Law No. 235 / 2004, the financial officer is required to check the information in the ZM or amending ZM, to remove any ambiguity and to use the information to determine the tax liability.
