The financial officer has to correct the data on deliveries of goods to other Member States in the ATIS system if:
- the controller does not prove the accuracy of the information reported in the ZM (or Amending ZM) and therefore corrects it by issuing an Amending ZM;
- the financial officer has demonstrated the inaccuracy of the information reported by the taxable person in the ZM or Amending ZM.
Notifications entered by the financial officer, without any corrective ZM being issued by the tax-payer, do not replace the tax-payer's pledge to provide a corrective ZM, but only lead to the correction of the data in the MIAS, so that they are current, complete and accurate.
The data from the ZM will be forwarded to the Member States concerned.
Only the national financial authority designated for cooperation with the other Member States in the field of VAT may transmit and receive this data.
This is the Clo (in the Czech Republic, this function is carried out by the Department of International Assistance in the field of VAT in the Ministry of Finance), and the "O _ MCTL" message is automatically sent to the Clo from the other Member States.
It contains all incorrect UST IDs specified in the transmitted ZM lines.
If the incorrect UST ID number is used in some of the transmitted lines of the ZM or the corrected ZM, an entry in the list of the wrong UST ID number is made.
The list contains a "Notice of doubt concerning UST-IdNr."
The financial officer checks the data and enters the result of the review into the system.
When purchasing goods from another Member State, the taxable person must state this in his VAT return and enter the value of the purchase in the lines of the VAT return for that purpose.
Selected cases of differences between the value of the purchases made by the Czech taxable person in his VAT return and the value of the goods delivered by the supplier from the other Member State in his ZM will be forwarded by the Clo to the competent FA for examination.
The staff there must investigate the discrepancies.
There can then be three different situations:
A) The value indicated by the Czech acquirer in the relevant headings of his VAT return is lower than the value of the deliveries indicated by suppliers from other EC Member States.
In this case, the financial officer checks the accuracy of the information.
B) The difference is zero.
This situation can be caused either by a change in the information within the EC (the foreign supplier corrects its ZM) or by a change in the information in the sales tax return (the Czech tax collector, meanwhile, makes a supplementary sales tax return on his own initiative).
In this case, it is at the discretion of the financial officer to check the accuracy of the information in the sales tax return.
C) The value of the goods purchased from other Member States, as indicated by the Czech taxable person in his VAT return, is higher than the value of the goods delivered by the suppliers of the other EC Member States.
This, in turn, is the discretion of the financial officer to verify the accuracy of the information.
After reviewing the differences and clarifying the reasons for their occurrence, the financial officer submits the results of his review to ATIS.
These results will be forwarded to the Clo.
