Submission and processing of summary reports in Germany
Entrepreneurs who make intra-Community deliveries from Germany to other EC Member States or participate in triangular transactions must hand over ZM quarterly, which lists intra-Community deliveries to purchasers (§ 18a (1) UStG).
The ZM must be delivered no later than the 10th day of the month following the calendar quarter in question.
If a permanent extension is granted for the levy of VAT pre-registration, this also applies to the ZM.
The ZM must be handed over to the Clo.
Since 1 January 2007, the electronic levy has been mandatory.
The FA responsible can allow exemptions for individual tax havens in order to avoid unreasonable hardship.
If the taxman finds that the ZM was faulty, he will be ploughed into submission of an Amending ZM within a month.
If the ZM is not handed over, the Clo will initiate an enforcement procedure.
This includes the following steps: - first reminder - second reminder, coupled with the threat that a penalty will be imposed and - fixing the penalty.
Although the German tax code allows a penalty of up to €25,000 (§ 329 AO) to be set, the Clo sets penalties of €125, 250 and 500 in three stages.
In addition, § 26a (1) No. 5 of the German Civil Code (UStG) stipulates that the taxable person acts in an unlawful manner if he intentionally or lightly fails to deliver a ZM correctly, not completely or in time, or if he does not correct a ZM or does not correct it in time.
This offence can be punishable by a fine of up to €5,000.
Data on intra-Community deliveries cannot be entered into the MIAS by the fä, because the Clo is exclusively responsible for the processing of the ZM.
The data of the ZM is only stored at the Clo.
The information from the summary messages is only available to the fä after their processing by the Clo.
The deadlines for processing ZM are laid down in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003.
The data of the ZM must be stored within three months of the relevant calendar quarter (in MIAS).
In the case of incorrect VAT ID number in the ZM of German taxpayers, the German Clo will receive a notification "O _ MCTL" from the other Member State.
The Clo then turns to the entrepreneur and asks for the right data.
If the Clo fails to obtain the correct information, the case will be referred to the relevant FA.
It is then up to him to request the correct information.
In the course of its audit, the BRH found that most entrepreneurs corrected the VAT ID number at the request of the Clo.
However, the memory, the threat and the imposition of up to three consecutive fines, takes too much time when a tax collector may be involved in cross-border carousel fraud.
The cases, which were ultimately reported to the relevant authorities, were usually closed within one to two months.
The FA, which is responsible for each case, refused to grant the tax exemption for the reported intra-Community deliveries in 73% of these cases.
If the taxman presented the correct VAT ID number, the FA asked him to submit a corrected ZM to the Clo because the FA could not correct the MIAS data itself.
The BRH found that neither the fä nor the Clo controlled the levy of the corrected ZM.
As the Clo does not have access to the data of the VAT returns, there is no comparison of the information provided in the VAT advance reports or the VAT return on goods deliveries with the corresponding information in the ZM before this data is sent to the Clo of the other Member States.
This comparison can only be made by the fä, which is usually done in preparation for a special VAT audit.
Data received from other Member States will be processed by the Clo.
Incorrect VAT ID numbers are detected and reported to the Member States concerned.
The data will be used to control labour market taxation in the fä.
As soon as they are available in the system, it compares the Clo with the data from previous calendar quarters.
If they meet certain criteria (see 5.2), control notifications will be prepared and sent to the relevant subject.
This happens on an ongoing basis, whereas a dissemination of the acquisition data of all persons subject to VAT will be produced later and forwarded to the fä.
The Risk Management System (RMS) for the investment process then compares this data with those for intra-Community acquisitions.
The system checks in full (only) those entrepreneurs who are not fully entitled to deduct VAT.
Comparison and evaluation
In the Czech Republic, tax payers who have made intra-Community deliveries to a person registered for VAT in another Member State will have to hand over a ZM to the local FA within 25 days of the end of the calendar quarter.
The fä process the ZM and forward the data to the Clo.
The values of intra-Community deliveries reported by the taxable persons in the ZM are compared with the values of intra-Community deliveries indicated by the same taxable persons in their VAT returns.
The results of the settlement will be taken into account in the context of the tax setting.
In Germany, taxable persons who have made intra-Community deliveries are required to pay quarterly ZM within the first 10 days of the following calendar quarter10.
Since 1 January 2007, the tax authorities have had to submit the ZM electronically to the Clo.
The data from the ZM are only available to the fä after their processing at the Clo.
In both the Czech Republic and Germany, the tax payers in the ZM only provide the goods.
The provision of services is not specified in the ZM. Unlike the Czech fä, the German fä cannot correct incorrect information in individual lines of the ZM.
Due to this limited access to the German MIAS data, incorrect UST ID numbers were not corrected even if the controller informed the FA of the correct UST ID number.
The German financial administration does not compare the information on intra-Community deliveries made by German tax-payers in their VAT pre-registration with the information provided by the relevant ZM.
Differences between the pre-registration data and the ZM are not regularly revealed before the German Clo transfers the MIAS data to other Member States.
Based on these findings by the BRH, it is obvious that a comparison would improve the reliability of the MIAS data transmitted.
In the Czech Republic, the data provided by other Member States on the supply of goods to Czech taxpayers is compared with the data on the purchases of goods provided by Czech tax authorities in their VAT returns.
The Czech Clo makes the comparison for each calendar quarter separately.
The most serious cases of deviations will be referred to the fä for examination.
Unlike the Czech financial administration, the German financial administration does not generally examine the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions.
Such general control will only be carried out in the case of taxable persons who are not fully entitled to the deduction.
In addition, the German tax administration only controls the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions of other taxable persons if the RMS produces an audit report or if the taxable person has already been selected for an audit.
This procedure relieves the fä from clarifying the reasons for any differences.
On the other hand, the detection of VAT fraud depends on the quality of the RMS.
In order to combat carousel fraud, updated information on intra-Community acquisitions must be available as early as possible.
The current system of ZM, in particular MIAS, provides financial authorities with information that may well be half a year old.
This delay could be reduced to up to four months if the tax-payers had to hand over monthly ZM.
The monthly levy would only marginally increase the bureaucratic burden, as most tax payers in the Czech Republic and Germany are already ploughed into issuing monthly sales tax returns or pre-registrations, and no more information is required for the ZM than for the sales tax returns or pre-registrations.
In order to avoid red tape, the levy of the ZM could be linked to the levy of sales tax declarations or advance declarations.
However, a levy on the monthly levy of ZM would create more periodic discrepancies between the information on intra-Community deliveries and those on intra-Community purchases, and would increase the flow of data between the Clo.
In 2006, the Federal Government considered the general introduction of monthly ZM.
The implementation failed due to the concerns of the federal states.
They feared that a monthly transfer of MIAS data to the Clo of other Member States could lead to misunderstandings and confusion.
In order to have an effect on the monthly levy of ZM, it is necessary to agree on the single monthly levy at European level, so that a monthly update of the MIAS data is possible.
