International exchange of information at level 3
Implementation of the international exchange of information in the Czech Republic
The international exchange of information allows financial officials to obtain information from other Member States on intra-Community transactions and on the tax payers who have carried them out.
Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 on mutual assistance in the field of VAT, repealing Directive (EEC) No 218 / 92 (hereinafter "Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003"), distinguishes between two basic types of exchange of information: The exchange of information on request and the spontaneous exchange of information (without prior request).
The international exchange of information on request takes place through a request for information (English: Request for information RFI) using the standardized SCAC form.
Financial officials in the Czech Republic will send their RFI or their replies to a RFI received by the Finance Directorate to the Clo, which will be responsible for translating the information provided in the standardised SCAC form into the foreign language and forwarding it to the other Member States.
In addition, the Clo receives requests for information (RFI) from other Member States and answers to requests sent. It provides for their translation into the Czech Republic and their distribution to the relevant subject for processing.
Article 8 of Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 sets a maximum period of three months from receipt of the request for its processing.
All RFI exchanged between the Czech Republic and Germany during the audited period were audited by the NKÚ.
Out of the total number of 94 RFI received from Germany, 70 cases (i.e. 74.5%) were dealt with within the three-month period; in a further 23 cases (i.e. 24.5%), this processing period was exceeded.
In the remaining one case, no reply had been sent to Germany until the NKÚ had examined it. More detailed information on the deadlines within which the Czech Republic responded to requests made by Germany can be found in Figure 2.
Out of the total number of 335 requests for information (RFI) sent to Germany from the Czech Republic, a response was received in 136 cases (i.e. 40.6%) within the three-month period; a further 179 (i.e. 53.4%) were processed after the expiry of this period and in 19 cases no response had yet been received from Germany at the time of the examination by the NKÚ (in the remaining one case, it was not possible to determine when Germany answered the request for information on the basis of the information provided).
