The international exchange of information without prior request is either automatic, structured automatically or in the form of spontaneous information.
Financial officials in other Member States are often provided with information without prior request, which is important for determining the VAT debt.
In the Czech Republic, all information is collected at the Clo.
The exchange of information between the individual Member States takes place electronically.
"Automatic exchange" under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 means the systematic transfer of previously defined information to other Member States at regular, pre-determined intervals without prior request.
"Structured automatic exchange" means the systematic transfer of previously defined information to another Member State without its prior request, once the relevant information is available.
The Czech Republic informs the other Member States in the automatic exchange of information on deliveries of new vehicles.
This information is obtained by the financial officer from the form notification of the delivery of a new vehicle in accordance with Section 19 of Law No. 235 / 2004 and from the copy of the invoice issued.
When processing this form, the financial officer will enter the required data into the relevant document template and forward it directly to the responsible employee of the Finance Directorate, where the data will be collected and sent to the Clo for further processing, after which the data will be transmitted to the other Member States within the specified period, at the latest within two months of the end of the quarter in which it was obtained.
The Czech Republic also provides information to other Member States on mail order transactions that are tax-free in the country of origin, on intra-Community transactions that appear to be inadmissible and on potential "missing traders."
This information will be transmitted to the other Member States via an SCAC form in a spontaneous exchange of information.
Implementation of the international exchange of information in Germany
In Germany, the initiative for requests for information and spontaneous exchange of information originates from the local FA.
The fä send the completed form SCAC 2004 by email directly to the German Clo, which forwards the SCACPreprints to the foreign Clo.
The fä are instructed to submit their requests for information or spontaneous information only in German, even the SCACVordruck used is in German.
Half of the German requests for information examined by the Federal Republic of Germany were sent in order to ensure income tax in the other Member State or to prove the tax freedom of intra-Community delivery from Germany to the other Member State.
If the German Clo receives a request for information from another Member State, it will check whether the value of the deliveries mentioned in the request exceeds the minimum amount of €15,000.
If there is no adequate justification for the request, the German Clo refuses to provide information on a turnover below the minimum threshold.
In addition, the German Clo provides for the translation of the freely worded texts in the SCAC form [(B1-17) or (E)], if they are neither written in German nor in English.
In response to the request for information, the Clo directs it to the relevant FA, referring to the three-month period.
No further deadlines have been set at the various levels of the German financial administration.
Although the German Clo has the technical means to monitor the keeping of deadlines, it does not have the necessary personnel capacity to remind the FA of the unfinished requests for information.
The fä receive the required information by writing to the controller or conducting an external audit.
The external auditors usually choose between two types of audit: The special VAT audit, which covers all taxable transactions within a period of several months, or the so-called VAT review, which may only refer to a recent transaction.
In this short and flexible form of audit, it is not necessary to make an announcement to the taxable person, and it has proved its worth in the investigation of a single turnover.
In the case of the automatic exchange of information, Germany will send the following information to the other Member State: - on VAT, which has been allocated to companies established in other EC Member States - on the reimbursement of VAT to companies established in other EC Member States.
In addition, Germany has pledged to provide the following information to the other EU Member States as part of the structured automatic exchange of information:
A. The delivery of new vehicles to entrepreneurs without UStIdNr., b. Distance sales (mail order) to other EC Member States that are not subject to VAT in Germany, c. Significant discrepancies between the purchases reported by a taxable person and the MIAS data transmitted by other Member States, i.e. intra-Community deliveries of items that have been improperly taxed by the taxable person in Germany, e. Potential "Missing Traders" who have made intra-Community transactions, regardless of whether their UStID number is still valid or has already been deleted, and f. Taxable persons who have made intra-Community deliveries to potential "Missing Traders" or to customers who have improperly used a VAT number.
Comparison and evaluation
The sending of requests for information and / or spontaneous information takes place both in the Czech Republic and in Germany on the initiative of the local authorities, who transmit the relevant SCAC forms to the Clo.
While the Czech Clo uses bilingual SCACPreprints (Czech-English) and translates the information provided into English or German, the German ones follow the instruction to submit requests for information or spontaneous information in a monolingual form only in German.
The German Clo does not produce translations of German texts.
When examining requests for information between the Czech Republic and Germany in the period 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005, the NKÚ found that the Czech financial administration completed 74.5% of the requests for information received within the three-month period, while the requests for information sent to Germany were only handled by the German financial administration in 40.6% of cases within that period.
Although the German Clo points to the three-month period, it does not monitor its compliance.
Due to the lack of memories, there is a high proportion of requests for information that are answered on time.
That is why the BRH has recommended a continuous reminder procedure to the German Clo.
The situation has now changed.
According to the information available to us, the German Clo is now reminding the tax authorities of the answer to the outstanding requests for information.
VAT risk management
Risk management in the Czech Republic
In the Czech Republic, several organisational units at different levels of financial management are involved in risk management in the area of VAT.
Within the Czech Ministry of Finance, the following organisational units are responsible for risk management and the fight against VAT fraud:
The Department of Methodology and Economic Administration of Value Added Tax, or its Risk Management Unit, is looking at identifying potential risk factors for tax revenue and evaluating trends in these risks in domestic and intra-Community trade.
At the national level, this body coordinates the requirements for the "credibility of VAT returns" criterion and uses the MIAS data to discover possible tax evasion in the context of intra-Community deliveries and acquisitions.
Based on data on the Czech Republic's trade balance, it evaluates risky goods, conceptually prepares risk management in the area of VAT and cooperates in this area with the relevant EC institutions and the other Member States.
The Department for International Assistance in the field of VAT provides, among other things, for the exchange of information, contributes to the creation and maintenance of a relevant information database, evaluates the data available in the MIAS system from other Member States, carries out public relations work and is responsible for other forms of intergovernmental assistance within the meaning of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003.
