The Tax Audit and Tax Investigation Methodology Department conducts risk analyses, among other things, within the framework of the methodical management of tax audits, sets priorities for the work planning of the financial directorates with regard to the selection of cases to be examined, produces risk analyses to combat tax evasion and, in this context, collects information from financial management and other sources and makes proposals for measures to combat tax evasion.
Tax investigators are in charge of the financial directorates. Their tasks include searching for tax-dodgers and industries that are risky in terms of the frequency of tax evasion (e.g. Internet transactions, gold, pharmaceutical industry), searching for unregistered tax-dodgers (e.g. in the Internet services, employment services, electronic and print media, etc.), investigating links in chain fraud cases and informing local financial authorities.
Special exam units have been set up in 12 selected subjects.
They have a regional competence and carry out tax audits outside the local area of competence of the fä, on the basis of appropriate authorisation.
The need to set up the special audit units arose from the increase in new and "improved" forms of tax evasion, particularly in connection with chain transactions.
These special units check according to the needs of tax investigators or focus on tax dodgers with certain activities, multinational companies and tax dodgers with particularly high turnover.
The following mechanisms for reducing the risks in the area of VAT have been integrated into the ATIS system: - the task of "credibility of VAT returns" to assess the risk effectiveness of tax returns issued; - the task of "selecting the taxable persons to be audited," selecting the taxable persons to be audited on the basis of certain criteria; - the task of "MIAS," which allows financial officials access to the data provided by the other EC Member States.
The "MIAS" task enables, among other things, the following: - verification of the validity of the VAT ID number of taxable persons from other Member States, - confirmation of the value of the goods delivered to a Czech taxable person, as indicated in the ZM by all suppliers of the taxable person in question from other Member States, - preparation of a list of taxable persons who have not provided ZM, - formal control of the information provided by taxable persons in the Czech Republic in their ZM before this information is transmitted to other Member States, - preparation of a list of taxable persons whose VAT returns do not match the information on goods delivered to other Member States with the information provided in the ZM, - preparation of a list of taxable persons whose tax returns are not in accordance with the value of the other Member States, the information on the value of the goods obtained from their suppliers in the other Member States.
As part of their mission to combat tax evasion, financial officials have access to data from state authorities such as the Commercial Register, Land Registry, Motor Vehicle Registry, Trade Registers, etc.
More detailed information can be found in Section 4.4.1 of the Comprehensive Notices in the Czech Republic.
Risk management in Germany
Due to their federal structure, both the federal financial authorities (in particular the Clo) and the financial administrations of the 16 federal states are involved in the development and introduction of an RMS in the Federal Republic of Germany.
Although there are joint working groups for development, neither the Clo nor the financial administrations of the federal states have a complete set of data.
At the level of the Clo, the unit ST I 2 (hereinafter referred to as the "Kuss" - Coordination Unit for Special Sales Tax Examinations and Tax Investigation Measures) collects the audit findings on fraud in the OPUS database.
In cooperation with the countries, another database called ZAUBER was set up for the kiss, where the tax authorities can enter and query the names of discovered missing traders or sales tax fraudsters.
The Kuss coordinates related cases of VAT fraud at the national level as well as cases of cross-border VAT fraud.
The experience of the kiss is brought into the development of the RMS through their cooperation in the working groups.
In addition, experts from several other organisational units of the Clo and the BMF are also involved.
The formal review of the composition of VAT numbers of other Member States, which appear in the ZM of German tax authorities, will be carried out at the Clo.
This formal review will take place prior to the transfer of the ZM to other Member States in order to improve the reliability of the MIAS data and thus its usefulness (see 4.4.2).
The validity of the UST ID number mentioned in the ZM will be assessed on the basis of the O _ MCTL identifiers provided by the other Member States (for the procedure of correcting invalid UST ID numbers, see also 4.4.2).
In addition, the Clo's RMS relies on the MIAS data provided by the other Member States and generates various types of communications for the discovery of suspected Missing Traders, using certain characteristics that usually occur in carousel transactions as clues.
Federal prosecutors are instructed to process these communications and, in certain cases, have to forward the outcome of their investigations to the Clo.
The BRH's audit has confirmed that all available features must be included in order to conclude with sufficient probability a case of tax fraud (rather than focusing mainly on a company's turnover).
Accordingly, the BRH has recommended that the BMF work with combinations of different clues in the preparation of the communications.
The risk management system should also take into account other clues, such as the payment behaviour of the tax-payer, the business sector or the company's shareholding relationships.
A second level of risk management is provided by the financial administrations of the federal states and focuses on the processing of sales tax filings and annual declarations.
For example, the system creates a list of those taxable persons who have indicated intra-Community deliveries in their VAT advance or annual declaration.
This list will be sent to the Clo to monitor the full delivery of the ZM.
Furthermore, in this type of risk management, the acquisitions given by the taxable person in his annual sales tax return are compared with the data in the MIAS.
The financial administrations of the federal states avoid comparing the quarterly data, as it would result in too many discrepancies due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud; e.g.:
- Suppliers and purchasers expect different times for the execution of intra-Community sales;
- different accounting and tax declarations of discounts and discounts.
In addition to comparing the data from the sales tax returns with the MIAS data, many federal states have certain risk management mechanisms, which are based on information in the sales tax returns and certain other clues (e.g. company word, age of the owner / shareholder, number of employees and method of payment of the tax payer).
Bavaria has introduced a risk management system based on fixed rules, which allows a team of tax fraud specialists (hereinafter referred to as "risk managers") to program their own rules in such a way as to identify suspected tax fraudsters.
This system is used in the processing of VAT advance notices.
This will give the relevant FA the advice of the RMS before the sales tax is set.
Since this system is not capable of learning, risk managers have to adjust the rules according to feedback from the fä.
Mecklenburg-Vorpommern has developed an adaptive neural network based on the data of uncovered cases.
Based on this data, the RMS is able to learn the characteristics of tax evasion.
The system creates a monthly list of tax cases where there is evidence of tax evasion.
On the basis of this list, the competent authorities will decide on the audit of the taxable persons concerned.
After the audit, the auditors must report their results so that the RMS can learn from the results of the audits it proposes.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, an adaptive neural network is used in combination with a rule-based fuzzy system.
Based on a lot of data from processed sales tax returns and some other clues, this neuro-fuzzy system (also known as the datamining system) calculates how likely a tax collector is to be involved in tax fraud.
It then creates a monthly list of suspected tax fraudsters.
On the basis of this list, the subjects select the relevant tax authorities for examination and report the audit results to the data centre in question.
The introduction of these three RMS is underway in the federal states.
Since each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three anti-fraud systems appears to be effective.
It remains to be seen whether the desired effects will materialise in actual use.
Comparison and evaluation
While it is not possible in this report to deal with the specific criteria of RMS in the Czech Republic and Germany, the NKÚ and the BRH have found that each Member State has developed its own RMS.
As well as the different approaches in the three German federal states mentioned above, the RMS of each European state has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
There is currently an exchange of experience between the financial authorities of the European Member States on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud.
VAT fraud - particularly carousel fraud - has proved to be not a national problem, but a European one.
The people involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one but in several Member States.
A Member State alone cannot develop an effective RMS.
Successful criteria, components or approaches to an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each EC Member State, and if this does not happen, fraudsters will seek out the Member State with the weakest RMS for their crimes.
The tax losses caused by Europe-wide VAT fraud do not necessarily affect the Member State in which the initiator is based.
Any other Member State involved in the fraud can be affected.
This is why there should be a European exchange of experience on the RMS.
Selected results from the audit of individual sales As part of the parallel audits, the NKÚ and the BRH examined the quality and usability of information on selected deliveries, respectively.
Acquisitions that were the subject of the international exchange of information between the financial administrations of the Czech Republic and Germany.
In addition, the two jurisdictions jointly examined the handling of several deliveries, which were in doubt about their implementation, or which the tax authorities of both states explained differently in the tax returns or in the ZM.
At the request of the BRH, the NKÚ investigated a total of eight business incidents between eight Czech and eight German tax authorities.
In addition, in 43 cases, the NKÚ examined the values of intra-Community transactions with Germany, as indicated by Czech tax authorities in their tax returns and ZM, on the basis of information provided by the BRH.
At the request of the NKÚ, the BRH reviewed a total of 23 deliveries between 23 German and 21 Czech taxpayers.
The relevant information was exchanged exclusively on the basis of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003 on the Clo.
The examination of the selected cases showed, among other things, that the different registration procedures in the EC Member States lead to the problems mentioned in Chapter 4.1:
1.
According to the MIAS data, in the third quarter of 2004, a Czech tax collector purchased goods worth €60,500 from a German tax collector.
When the Czech taxpayer declared a purchase of only €29,869, the Czech financial administration sent a request for information to Germany in order to verify the value of the goods delivered.
In its response to the Czech request for information, the German side said that the German taxpayer in question had delivered goods worth €27,381 to his Czech business partner in the 2nd quarter of 2004, goods worth €31,997 in the third quarter and goods worth €10,276 in the fourth quarter.
The answer also revealed that the VAT ID number of the German taxable person was not valid until 28 September 2004, but the German Clo had accepted another request from the German taxable person and had retroactively brought forward the validity of the VAT ID number as of 1 May 2004.
The German tax authority corrected the ZM.
On the basis of this information, it was a (intra-Community) acquisition of goods by the Czech taxpayer.
In a request to the relevant tax office in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that in 2004 the Czech taxable person had issued supplementary VAT returns for the individual (under-age) tax periods in which he declared a higher value of purchases from other Member States, while at the same time seeking the deduction of VAT from purchases from other Member States.
On the basis of these additional sales tax declarations, the competent representative of the Czech tax office could not clearly determine whether the declared acquisitions also included the value of the deliveries of the above-mentioned German supplier.
In response to a request for information from the NKÚ, the BRH found that the German supplier had been registered in September 2003 as subject to sales tax.
At the time of registration, however, he had not applied for the allocation of a VAT ID number, but only a tax number that was finally valid for Germany.
Although in Germany it is usually not possible to retroactively allocate a VAT ID number to a taxable person, in 2006 the responsible person in charge of the German financial administration did so retroactively on 1 May 2004.
The German Clo retrospectively allocates a VAT ID number if the German entrepreneur did not cause the delayed allocation; for example, if the Clo caused the delay following the request of the taxable person to grant a VAT ID number.
In this case, the Clo retroactively grants the VAT ID number, because the entrepreneur does not need a valid VAT ID number for an intra-community delivery, according to § 6 UStG.
Conversely, a German acquirer does not need the (valid) VAT ID number of its supplier to declare the intra-Community acquisition.
Due to these procedural differences between the Member States, the German Clo retroactively granted the VAT ID number in this particular case.
2.
As part of the international exchange of information, the Czech financial officer asked for a review of the German entrepreneur's sales tax registration.
According to the MIAS data, the date of registration is 5 March 2005, while a registration certificate issued by the local German FA indicates 1 October 2004.
In their response, the German authorities announced that the German taxpayer had been registered on 1 October 2004, but for organisational reasons had only been allocated a VAT ID number in Germany on 16 February 2005.
Through a request to the local Czech financial officer, the NKÚ learned that the financial officer had carried out a VAT audit on the Czech taxable person for the tax periods from the third quarter of 2004 to the second quarter of 2005.
During this audit, the tax office found that the Czech taxable person had declared in his VAT return services worth CZK 9,897, which he had provided to the German taxable person prior to his VAT registration (i.e. before 1 October 2004).
The (Czech) Tax Office fixed a tax debt of CZK 1,880 for the third quarter of 2004 in relation to the Czech taxpayer.
On the basis of the NKÚ request, the BRH found that the German taxpayer had only been allocated the VAT ID number when he applied to the FA on 16 February 2005 for his company, which was founded in 2004.
In addition, the FA retroactively registered him from 1 October 200415 for the purposes of VAT, in order to be able to monitor the levy of the VAT return for 2004.
In this VAT return, the taxable person indicated intra-Community purchases from the Czech Republic worth 160 €(approx. 5,000 CZK).
3. In his VAT return for September 2004 as well as in his ZM for the third quarter of 2004, a Czech tax collector gave goods worth CZK 114,615 to a German tax collector.
When reviewing the registration of the German taxable person in the MIAS system, the Czech financial officer found that this registration was only valid from 11 November 2004 and therefore after the goods were delivered to Germany.
The Czech tax collector issued a supplementary sales tax return in which he declared sales from domestic deliveries worth CZK 114,615 and sales tax of CZK 21,777, which he paid.
In a request to the local FA in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that the Czech taxman subsequently submitted a request for the resumption of the tax procedure in respect of the supplementary VAT return, as evidence he submitted a confirmation from the German financial administration that the German taxable person had been registered since 1 January 2000.
Accordingly, the Czech financial officer reviewed the validity of the registration of the German taxable person in the context of the international exchange of information.
According to the German information, the German taxpayer was not assigned a VAT ID number until 11 November 2004, i.e. after the date of delivery of the goods.
As a result, the Czech finance official rejected the request to reopen the tax procedure.
The BRH found that in this case no intra-Community purchase of goods had taken place, because the German taxable person had only received a VAT ID number on 11 November 2004.
However, the German beneficiary explained both the acquisition as an intra-Community acquisition and the VAT on it, and also demanded the reimbursement of taxes of the same amount.
Because this did not lead to a change in the amount of the German tax payer's tax liability, the German financial officer did not correct the information in the VAT return.
Furthermore, the BRH found that the company of the German taxman mentioned in the request for information was changed during the processing of the answer in Germany, which led to confusion between two German tax authorities.
This change in the name of the German taxman also confused the Czech financial officer.
4.
As part of the international exchange of information, the German financial officer reviewed the purchase of goods in the first quarter of 2005 by a Czech tax collector from a German tax collector worth €22,686.
In a request to the local tax officer in the Czech Republic, the NKÚ found that the Czech financial officer had examined, in the course of an external audit with the Czech tax authority, whether the intra-Community delivery had actually taken place and whether the Czech taxman had booked and paid the invoice for the delivery of the goods.
The Czech tax collector did not declare the intra-Community acquisition in his sales tax return, because the German supplier did not specify his VAT ID number in the invoice, but only his tax number for transactions within Germany.
According to the MIAS data, the German taxable person will not be registered for VAT in connection with intra-Community sales until 21 April 2005, i.e. after delivery to the Czech taxable person.
The Czech finance official also requested that the German financial administration send a copy of the registration certificate of the German tax collector, so that he could, if necessary, initiate an appropriate tax procedure.
The Czech FA considered this business to be the purchase of goods from a non-entrepreneurial (private) person in Germany and therefore did not impose VAT on the purchase of goods from Germany.
The BRH found that under German law, a taxable person who delivers goods to other Member States does not have to have a VAT ID number for intra-Community deliveries in order to be able to claim the VAT exemption for such deliveries.
The supplier must only have the purchaser's VAT number in the other Member State and be able to prove the transport of the goods in question to the other Member State.
In this case, according to German tax law, turnover is a (tax-exempt) intra-Community supply, which should be subject to income tax in the Czech Republic.
In any case, it is important that the Czech financial officer took note of this business incident because the delivery of a machine of this value was not part of the core business of the German supplier.
As described in Section 4.6.2, the German Clo rejects requests for information on intra-Community sales if they are below the minimum threshold of €15,000:5.
According to the MIAS data, in the third quarter of 2004, a Czech tax collector purchased goods worth €12,561 from a German tax collector.
The Czech financial officer carried out an audit for this tax period.
As part of the intergovernmental assistance, the Czech financial administration asked for the examination of this supply of goods by means of an SCAC form.
