According to the Czech tax authority, however, the goods were not delivered from Germany to the Czech Republic, but were resold in Germany in 2005.
The Czech taxpayer provided evidence of the sale in January 2005.
The Czech taxable person was not registered as a taxable person in Germany and had not taxed the sale of the goods in question either in the Czech Republic or in Germany.
All of these facts pointed to tax evasion within Germany and the Czech finance official provided this information in his response to the request for information to the German financial administration.
In a request to the local Czech financial officer, the NKÚ found that the Czech tax collector had issued a supplementary tax return for the fourth quarter of 2004 on the basis of a tax audit, in which he declared, among other things, the value of the goods he had purchased from a German tax collector and at the same time asserted the right of deduction for the acquisition from other Member States.
In his Czech VAT return, he did not declare VAT on the sale of goods in Germany.
On the basis of a supplementary sales tax return issued after the external audit, the Czech financial officer fixed the VAT debt unchanged.
According to Czech law, in this case, there was no purchase of goods from other Member States, as the goods were not shipped or transported from another Member State to the Czech Republic.
As a result, the Czech financial officer came to the wrong conclusion during the external audit.
The BRH found that immediately after receiving the reply to the request for information, which showed that the goods had not left Germany, the German tax officer corrected the tax return and demanded the payment of VAT worth €1,600.
In addition, the relevant FA sent a control notice to the FA responsible for the actual recipient of the goods to ensure that the resale of these goods is properly taxed.
In the following cases, operators declared intra-Community deliveries that may not have been carried out:
18.
The Czech finance official received a request for information from the German financial administration on whether the Czech taxman had purchased a car worth €47,400 from the German taxman in February 2005.
The request for information was accompanied as an attachment by an imprint of the VAT registration certificate of the Czech taxpayer.
A photocopy of the passport of the person who was supposed to have transferred the vehicle was also attached to the facility.
In the course of his investigation, the Czech financial officer found that the passport had been stolen, that the person named in it had not brought a vehicle into the Czech Republic and indicated that he had no contact with a German tax collector.
The VAT registration certificate, the print of which had been sent by the German side, had not been issued by the Czech financial administration.
With this information, the Czech finance official answered the request for information and said at the same time that he could not confirm the purchase of the car.
In a request to the local Czech financial officer, the NKÚ found that the Czech tax officer is not based at the address indicated in the commercial register and that the company's managing director is not available.
Following a tax complaint procedure for the tax period in February 2005, the Czech financial officer fixed the tax liability of the Czech taxman at zero.
In the course of a further investigation, the Czech finance official found that the vehicle in question had been sold to another Czech person who had purchased it on the basis of an internet advertisement.
The BRH found that the local German financial officer had rejected the German tax payer's claim to exempt this delivery from VAT due to the Czech response to the request for information.
19. In the course of an external audit, a German FA was unable to clarify a difference of €3,000 between the value of the goods purchased in the VAT return and the reported values from other Member States.
In the fourth quarter of 2004 and in the first quarter of 2005, a Czech tax collector was supposed to have delivered goods worth €89,424 to a German tax collector.
As the acquisition declared by the German tax-payer was not in line with the MIAS data, the German financial officer asked for the verification of deliveries and their payment as part of the interstate exchange of information.
In his reply to the request for information, the Czech finance official said that the only managing director of the Czech company had been deleted from the commercial register on 8 July 2005 and that a new managing director had not yet been registered.
The German recipient of the goods was presumed to be a relative of the shareholder of the Czech company.
The Czech tax collector issued a VAT return and a ZM, which was signed by an unauthorised person, namely the company's shareholder, after the deletion of the managing director in the commercial register.
The accountant of the Czech taxman told the financial officer that the owner of the capital had deposited the payment received for the invoiced goods in euros into the company's account.
Cash receipts were not issued.
In a request to the local Czech FA, the NKÚ found that the financial officer had recognised the Czech taxable person's claim for VAT exemption for goods deliveries to other Member States, worth CZK 1,326,307 in the first quarter of 2004 and CZK 1,416,180 in the first quarter of 2005.
The BRH found that the German financial officer did not correct the German acquirer's sales tax return, as in the meantime a German court had confirmed the insolvency of the German taxpayer.
Since the previous external audit showed no signs of tax fraud, there is no prospect of actually being able to collect a fixed VAT debt.
20. According to the MIAS data, a German tax collector purchased goods from the Czech Republic worth €4,251,196 in 2005, after which he had purchased goods worth €43,274 in the previous year.
The German taxpayer did not declare the intra-Community acquisitions in his 2004 VAT return or in his 2005 tax return.
In addition, he did not declare any value-related outputs.
Due to these discrepancies, the German FA submitted a request for information concerning the 4th quarter of 2005 and the 1st quarter of 2006.
In the ZM for these two quarters, a Czech supplier reported intra-Community deliveries of goods totalling CZK 167,246,083.
On 6 September 2006, the request for information was received, in which the German side asked to check whether the delivery reported by the Czech tax authorities had actually taken place.
In response to this request for information, the Czech financial administration said that the German request could not be met because the Czech company did not have a managing director (or other legal representatives).
The documents provided to the NKÚ by the relevant financial officer show that, together with the managing director of the Czech tax authority, a protocol was drawn up on 30 March 2006 on the commencement of the VAT audit for the 4th quarter of 2004 and the period January to December 2005.
At the same time, the tax payer was asked by the financial officer to submit all accounting and tax documents for this period, but failed to do so.
According to the Commercial Register, the term of office of the only managing director expired on 16 May 2005, without the appointment of a new managing director.
The Czech taxpayer has not issued any sales tax returns since April 2006.
As part of the parallel investigation, the NKÚ, in cooperation with the BRH, investigated several cases of intra-Community deliveries between the Czech Republic and Germany, which were not the subject of a previous exchange of information between the two countries.
The two auditors exchanged information on the cases under review through the Clo of both countries.
21. A Czech company (UCR), which is not based in Germany, informed the competent FA (Chemnitz-Süd) that it wanted to do tax-exempt business in Germany.
Based on this information, the company was registered as of June 2005, but did not receive a German VAT ID.
The (UCR) accepted an order from a Danish company (UDK) for the production of wind turbines and for their delivery to Austria on behalf of, at the risk and on behalf of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient production capacity of its own, the Danish company passed on part of the order to a German tax authority (UDE) based in Germany.
The following illustration shows the contractual relations and the transport route of the wind turbines:
According to German law, the place of performance of these transactions must be determined as described below:
- The Danish company (UDK) sent the wind turbines to Austria for installation on its behalf, at its risk and for its own account.
Due to the installation, its delivery takes place in Austria, i.e. the delivery of the wind turbines is controllable in Austria.
- Because the freight forwarder was commissioned by the Danish company (UDK) and the latter had the transport carried out on his own behalf, at his own risk and for his own account, the place of delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE) is where the transport started, i.e. in Germany.
Although the wind turbines were delivered to another EC Member State (AU) and the receiver is registered as taxable in an EC Member State (CR), no tax exemption could be claimed for the delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE), since the EC Member State for which the delivery was intended is a different country from the seat state of the Czech company 19.
Accordingly, the delivery is duly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (UCR) claimed the deduction in its sales tax returns.
The place of delivery of the Czech company (UCR) also depends on the place where the transport started.
However, some of the wind turbines were transported from the Czech Republic and others from Germany.
- The delivery of wind turbines manufactured in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
- The delivery of the remaining wind turbines, which were manufactured in Germany, took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) delivered intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic to Austria as well as intra-Community deliveries from Germany to Austria.
The BRH found that the Czech company (UCR) did not declare intra-Community deliveries in its German tax returns or in its ZM issued to the German Clo.
Thus, the Czech company may have treated all its intra-Community supplies uniformly as intra-Community supplies from the Czech Republic.
The NKÚ found that (UCR) did not report intra-Community deliveries to Austria, but intra-Community deliveries to Denmark.
In order to ensure the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions in Austria, the cooperation of at least four financial administrations (the Austrian, Czech, Danish and German) would be necessary, although in this case there is no evidence of tax fraud or tax evasion.
In addition, the NKÚ and the BRH examined case designs to show the size of the differences between the data in the VAT returns and the MIAS data caused by the different legislation of 2004.
The audited cases also show that it takes some time for the tax-payers and the tax payers to apply the new legal requirements:
22. In its ZM for the second, third and fourth quarters of 2004, a Czech tax collector reported shipments of goods totalling CZK 792,977,452 to a German tax collector.
In the same period, another Czech tax collector reported intra-Community deliveries in his ZM to another German tax collector with a total value of CZK 18,157,265.
The information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ showed that in both cases it was electricity supplies.
Both Czech taxpayers took into account the above deliveries in their ZM in accordance with Czech Law No. 235 / 2004, which was in force in 2004.
In a further review of these transactions, an audit group of the NKÚ found that in 2004, different legal requirements were in place for the supply and acquisition of electrical energy between the Czech Republic and Germany.
While in the Czech Republic the tax authorities declared the supplies of electrical energy to be intra-Community supplies of goods in accordance with the provisions of Law No. 235 / 2004, which were in force in 2004, according to German legislation, it was not an intra-Community purchase of goods, but taxable and taxable sales in Germany.
The differences in the legal provisions were eliminated in the Czech Republic by the adoption of Law No 635 / 2004, which amended some tax provisions with effect from 1 January 2005.
23. In the examination of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions in cooperation with the BRH, it was further established that a Czech tax collector declared intra-Community deliveries to a German tax collector for the first and fourth quarters of 2005 totalling CZK 240,411,163 and another Czech tax collector in his ZM for the same period intra-Community deliveries to another German tax collector worth CZK 263,470,776.
Information provided by the BRH to the NKÚ showed that in both cases it was a supply of electrical energy.
In accordance with the wording of Law 235 / 2004, which will apply from 1 January 2005, the place of performance for the supply of electrical energy shall be the place where the acquirer has his legal headquarters, his registered office or his place of business for which this delivery is made.
For this reason, the Czech tax authorities should not have specified the electricity supplies in their ZM for 2005.
The fact that both controllers treated the supply of electrical energy in their ZM as intra-community supplies led to a difference of 503,881,939 CZK in MIAS.
Closing remarks
The cooperation has achieved the objectives of the BRH and the NKÚ.
Both auditors gained in-depth knowledge of VAT management systems in the Czech Republic and Germany.
The cooperation revealed differences in the two systems and in the legal regulations governing the VAT administration.
During the parallel tests, interesting cases of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions came to light.
Some of them are worth watching.
On the basis of the audit results, both auditors drew up recommendations on the management of VAT.
The follow-up of these recommendations in the form of a review should be part of the follow-up.
The new experience and knowledge gained through the cooperation of both auditors is the basis for the successful implementation of future audits in the field of VAT administration.
